WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.393
Consider this contrasting case: Strategy A: An AppsFlyer seller pitches

00:00:04.393 --> 00:00:08.787
the technical superiority of our attribution models to an AWS

00:00:08.787 --> 00:00:13.180
Account Manager. Strategy B: An AppsFlyer seller demonstrates how our

00:00:13.180 --> 00:00:17.574
platform scales the customer's marketing operations, thereby increasing the volume

00:00:17.574 --> 00:00:21.967
of data generated and scaling the customer's overall AWS compute

00:00:21.967 --> 00:00:26.360
utilization. Which strategy succeeds? Pause here and privately write down

00:00:26.360 --> 00:00:30.754
your justification for which approach will secure the Account Manager's

00:00:30.754 --> 00:00:35.147
support before continuing. Strategy B succeeds because it aligns directly

00:00:35.147 --> 00:00:39.541
with the governing incentive structure. To secure this critical internal

00:00:39.541 --> 00:00:43.934
advocacy, you must highlight that our marketplace revenue is skyrocketing

00:00:43.934 --> 00:00:48.328
at four times year-over-year growth, with average won opportunities frequently

00:00:48.328 --> 00:00:52.721
exceeding four hundred and fifty thousand dollars. Most crucially, emphasize

00:00:52.721 --> 00:00:57.114
that we provide Amazon an invaluable, highly coveted entry point

00:00:57.114 --> 00:01:01.508
into enterprise marketing departments. As AppsFlyer successfully scales a customer's

00:01:01.508 --> 00:01:05.901
marketing operations, the massive volume of data generated will inevitably

00:01:05.901 --> 00:01:10.295
scale the customer's overall infrastructure account as a highly profitable,

00:01:10.295 --> 00:01:14.688
undeniable result.
